Project Foundations for Data Science: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 40

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Question 13: The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer¶

In [ ]:
# We only want the restaurants with ratings.
df_rate = df[df['rating'] != 'Not given'].copy()

# Rating is an object, so we have to convert it to an integer in order to find the average.
df_rate['rating'] = df_rate['rating'].astype('int')

# We need the data to be grouped by restaurant name and the amount of ratings in order to find which ones have above 50 ratings.
rcount = df_rate.groupby(['restaurant_name'])['rating'].count().sort_values(ascending = False).reset_index()

#We can display the first 5 restaurants since the data is sorted, as you can see only the first 4  fufill the first part of the criteria

# We can get the names of the restauraants with a count above 50 here to filter out the others.
rest_above_50 = rcount[rcount['rating']>50]['restaurant_name'] ## Complete the code to get the restaurant names having rating count more than 50

#Use the variable above to copy only the restaurants with above 50 count into the new dataframe.
rating_avg_4 = df_rate[df_rate['restaurant_name'].isin(rest_above_50)].copy()

# We can group the data by restaurant names and rating average now because we know every restaurant included is above 50 in count.
rating_avg_4.groupby(['restaurant_name'])['rating'].mean().sort_values(ascending = False).reset_index().dropna()

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders¶

In [ ]:
#Displays the total revenue that the company receives from orders.
def net_rev(ordercost): #function calculates the revenue per order.
    if ordercost > 20:
        return ordercost * 0.25
    elif ordercost > 5:
        return ordercost * 0.15
    else:
        return ordercost * 0
#Prints the total revenue they receive towards all orders.
print('The total revenue the company receives is $',round(sum(df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(net_rev)), 2))

The total revenue the company receives is $ 6166.3

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations)¶

Conclusions:¶

  • The data set includes 1898 orders, 1200 unique customers who have ordered, 178 unique restaurants to order from, and 14 unique cuisine types.
  • 736 orders include no rating, which is 38.8% of orders.
  • The most popular cuisine on the weekend or weekdays is American.
  • 29.24 percent of orders cost more than 20 dollars and 70.76 percent of orders are 20 dollars or under.
  • The average time it takes to deliver an order is 24 minutes.
  • The top 3 customers have ordered 13, 10, and 9 orders.
  • French is the highest average costing cuisine type.
  • Spanish is the highest average rating cuisine type.
  • The weekend orders have a higher average cost than the weekday orders
  • Weekend orders take 22 minutes on average to deliver and weekday orders take 28 minutes on average.
  • There seems to be no correlation between order cost, food preparation time, and delivery time.
  • The top 10 restaurants in highest average cost are Kami Ramen House, Emporio, Bhatti Indian Grill, Haru Gramercy Park, Lucky Strike, ll Bambino, Sarabeths, Rohm Thai, Klong, and 67 Burger.
  • The top 5 restaurants with the highest number of ratings are Shake Shack, Meatball Shop, Blue Ribbon Sushi, Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken, and RedFarm Broadway.
  • The company total revenue for all the orders included was 6,166.30 dollars.
  • 10.54 percent of orders take more than 60 minutes to make.

Recommendations:¶

Application Reccomendations

  • Promote higher rated restaurants more like Shake Shack, Meatball Shop, Blue Ribbon Sushi, Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken, and RedFarm Broadway with a feature restaurants page within the app.
  • There should be a categories section within the app to find what type of cuisine you are looking for. Within this categories section should have a featured cuisines area where high rated cuisines can be found and promoted from different restaurants.
  • Drivers who work for the company should only be allowed to drive if they have a good rate of orders arriving on time. This promotes speed and lowering average delivery time. Once you have reached below a set percentage of orders delivered within time, you will be removed as a driver.
  • Include a section that can track the analytics of restaurants and their average ratings, cost, and time to deliver and prepare food. Make this available for the restaurants, so they can see these analytics and improve themselves for deliveries through the app. Let companies interact with their own restaurant sections in order to be more involved and to care more about the analytics within the application.
  • Use an Algorithm to show restaurants that customers frequent often or cuisines that the customer has spent more money on (For example, a customer spends majority of his money in the app on American cuisine, so promote high rated American cuisines to him).

Promotion Reccomendations

  • A loyalty system should be introduced with reward points that you build up from ordering from a restaurant multiple times. This also promotes more reocurring orders.
  • There should be a discount reward system introduced that can help promote more ratings being given. After a certain number of ratings given within the app after orders, a discount code can be given for a certain cuisine type of restaurant. This also could be just a discount on the overall order cost.
  • (Promotion) Drivers should be rewarded with a bonus for completing more orders to provide incentive to drivers to finish orders at a faster rate. This can help bring down the total time it takes to make a delivery. This can be more emphasized during the week in order to lower the weekday delivery time.
  • Lower rated restaurants and restaurants with the least orders should be promoted less within the app and give notification that they are.
